1 Pivoting and Wide and Narrow Data Formats

Additional reading:

  • Wickham and Grolemund on pivoting, or
  • Baumer, Kaplan, and Horton on reshaping data

As we are transforming data, it is important to keep in mind what constitutes each case (row) of the data. For example, in the initial sample data below, each case is a single category-quarter combination.

Table 1.1: Each case is one category-quarter combination.
category quarter amount
A Q1 9.56
A Q2 7.36
A Q3 0.28
A Q4 9.79
B Q1 8.42
B Q2 9.19
B Q3 1.47
B Q4 5.57
C Q1 1.28
C Q2 0.06
C Q3 6.77
C Q4 5.74

It is often necessary to rearrange your data in order to create visualizations, run statistical analysis, etc. We have already seen some ways to rearrange the data to change the case. For example, what is the case after performing the following command?

DFTotal<-DF %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(amount))

Each case now represents one a category:

Table 1.2: Narrow format where each case is just a category.
category total
A 26.99
B 24.65
C 13.85

In this activity, we are going to learn two new operations to reshape and reorganize the data: pivot_wider() and pivot_longer().

1.1 Wider

We’d like to transform the data into a wide format with each of the possible values of the quarter variable becoming its own column. The operation we need to perform this transformation is pivot_wider(). It takes a values_from (amount in this case) representing the variable to be divided into multiple new variables, and a names_from (the original variable quarter in this case) that identifies the variable in the initial narrow format data whose values should become the names of the new variables in the wide format data. The names_sort=TRUE dictates that the variables are listed in alphabetical order; when it is FALSE, they are listed in order of first appearance.

DFWide<-DF %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from=quarter,values_from=amount,names_sort=TRUE)
Table 1.3: A wide format with one case per category.
category Q1 Q2 Q3 Q4
A 9.56 7.36 0.28 9.79
B 8.42 9.19 1.47 5.57
C 1.28 0.06 6.77 5.74

Now let’s add a new column that has the total values for the two halves of the year:

DFWide<-DFWide%>%
  mutate(H1=Q1+Q2,H2=Q3+Q4)
Table 1.4: A wide format with one case per category and two new columns.
category Q1 Q2 Q3 Q4 H1 H2
A 9.56 7.36 0.28 9.79 16.92 10.07
B 8.42 9.19 1.47 5.57 17.61 7.04
C 1.28 0.06 6.77 5.74 1.34 12.51

Aside: If instead we wanted the categories across the top as variables and the quarters as the rows, we could pivot_wider() on the category variable:

DFWide2<-DF %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from=category,values_from=amount,names_sort=TRUE)
Table 1.5: A wide format with one case per quarter.
quarter A B C
Q1 9.56 8.42 1.28
Q2 7.36 9.19 0.06
Q3 0.28 1.47 6.77
Q4 9.79 5.57 5.74

1.2 Longer

To switch back from a wider format to a narrower format, we can use the following pivot_longer() operation. It gathers the columns listed c(Q1,Q2,Q3,Q4,H1,H2) under the cols argument into a single column whose name is given by the names_to argument (“time_period”), and includes the values in a column called total, which is the input to the values_to argument.

DFNarrow<-DFWide %>%
  pivot_longer(cols=c(`Q1`,`Q2`,`Q3`,`Q4`,`H1`,`H2`),names_to="time_period",values_to="total")
# we could also specify `cols=-category` or `cols=starts_with(c("Q","H"))`
Table 1.6: Narrow format where each row is a category-time_period pair, where the time period is either a quarter or a half.
category time_period total

A Q3 0.28
A Q4 9.79

A H2 10.07

B H1 17.61
B H2 7.04

3 Crop Yields

As shown in the following graphic from Our World in Data, one of the historical causes of deforestation has been using more land to grow crops:

An important way to slow this trend is by improving crop yields: how much of a crop can be produced annually on a fixed size of land (e.g., a hectare). In addition to slowing deforestation, improving crop yields has important consequences in food security, health outcomes, economic sustainability, and habitat preservation.

Thankfully, crop yields have increased significantly over the last century, due primarily to agricultural technology improvements that are collectively referred to as the Green Revolution. Our World in Data writes:

“The Green Revolution is used to describe the large-scale transfer and adoption of new technologies in the agricultural sector, particularly in the developing world. These technologies included chemical inputs (such as fertilizers and pesticides), irrigation technologies, farm mechanization (such as tractors), and high-yielding rice, wheat and maize seed varieties.”

Our World in Data editor and Not the End of the World author Hannah Ritchie shows how much cropland these increases in productivity have spared in the following chart (source):

In this activity, we are going to further explore trends in crop yields from 1961-2021. We’ll use data from the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), loaded in the following code chunk:

crops<-read_csv("http://faculty.olin.edu/dshuman/DS/Production_Crops_Livestock_E_All_Data.csv")%>%
  janitor::clean_names()
names(crops) <- sub('^y', '', names(crops))

The following graphic depicts how Mexico’s cereal production life cycle has changed over the course of 1960-2020. From the data, we can see that since the 60s, production and yield of the product has increased. The area harvested, on the other hand, has fluctuated since the 60s. Exercise 4.2 (Wrangling practice) Starting from the crops data (79606 observations of 195 variables), do the following:

  • Keep only the rows corresponding to area_code 5000, 5100, 5203, 5204, 5207, 5300, 5400, 5500 (continents or larger regions)
  • Keep only the rows corresponding to yields, not land used or total production
  • Delete all of the year columns that end in “f” (note codes) or “n” (normalized data)
  • Delete all of the data associated with 2022 (too much missing data for that year)
  • Only keep the data for the following crops: Wheat, Vegetables Primary, Rice, Maize (corn), Apples, and Soya beans
  • Delete the following variables: area_code_m49, item_code_cpc, element_code, element, unit
  • Store the resulting table as crops2

After all of that, your crops2 table should end up with 48 rows and 65 variables. Check that this is the case before moving on.

crops2 <- 
  crops %>%
  filter(area_code %in% c(5000, 5100, 5203, 5204, 5207, 530, 5400, 5500), element %in% 'Yield') %>% # only taking area_codes listed 
  select(-ends_with('f'), -ends_with('n'), -"2022") %>% # getting rid of columns w f and n on the end, and also 2022 
  filter(item %in% c("Cereals n.e.c.", "Wheat", "Vegetables Primary", "Rice", "Maize (corn)", "Apples", "Soya beans")) %>% # only taking items of this type 
  select(-area_code_m49, -item_code_cpc, -element_code, -element, -unit) # getting rid of more columns, using - to indicate delete

Exercise 4.4 (Historical crop trends) Visualize the data from crops2 in a single graphic, as follows:

  • There should be 6 facets - one for each crop - stacked on top of each other
  • Each facet should contain a plot with the year on the x-axis (1961-2021), the yield on the y-axis, and 8 separate lines, one for each of the regions we selected
  • The line colors should be different for each region and labeled in a legend
  • The units of the y-axis should be tonnes/hectare

Some hints for this exercise:

  • You can find plots like this for a single crop at a time on Our World in Data
  • A good first step is probably to draw a rough sketch on paper
  • You will have to do some pivoting to get the crops data into glyph-ready format (one row per glyph); before you start pivoting, think about how you want the data to end up in order to be ready to send to ggplot
  • The y-axis of the plot should be tonnes/hectare, but that is not the unit given in crops, so you will have to do some unit conversion
  • The yields are quite different for each crop, so you want to let the y-axis scales be different for each facet
  • ggplot will do a better job of automatically labeling the years on the x-axis if you first convert the years from character strings to doubles with as.double
  • For line colors that are easier to tell apart, I used the scale_color_lancet() function from the ggsci package
crops4 <- pivot_longer(crops2, '1961' : '2021', names_to="year")  # add a table w years, and corresponding value. this increases # rows

  ggplot(crops4, aes(x=year, y=value, color=area))+ # year on x, yield on y, and coloring based on region 
    geom_line(aes(group = area))+ # r cant make assumption about which lines to make even w facets/color differentiation, therefore specify the lines grouping
    facet_grid(rows=vars(item),scales="free")+ # scaling each facet based on values, each crop type is the type of facet 
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, size=5))+ # rearranging x axis text so its easier to read 
    labs(x="Year", y="Yield", title="Yield of Crop from the Years 1961 to 2021")


Exercise 4.5 (Computing compound annual growth rates) Now let’s compute some metrics associated with the graphs above. The compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of a quantity is the percent it grows each year, on average, assuming compounding. For example, if you start with a value of 100 at time 0 and the three-year CAGR is 2.5%, then the value after three years is 100*(1+.025)*(1+.025)*(1+.025)=107.69.

Use pivoting and wrangling commands to start from crops2 and make and print a table with eight rows (one for each region) and three columns: the region name, the CAGR of Maize (corn) from 1961-2021, and the CAGR of Wheat from 1961-2021. If you want to make it look nicer, you can use the command percent(x,accuracy=.01) which takes whatever is in x and converts it to a percentage with two decimals.

crops_CAGR <- 
  crops2 %>%
  select(area, item, "1961", "2021") %>% # select which columns i want to keep
  filter(item %in% c("Maize (corn)", "Wheat")) %>%
  mutate(CAGR=percent(((`2021`/`1961`)^(1/60)) - 1, accuracy=0.1)) %>% # calculate CAGR and put into a column, note that numerical column names have to be specified w '' instead of ""
  select(-"1961", -"2021") %>% # getting rid of value columns 
  pivot_wider(names_from=item, values_from = CAGR) # making items into columns filled w CAGR values
